#### GDP per capita (nominal)

Similarly, the historical evolution of GDP per capita (Nominal) for the Democratic Republic of the Congo, spanning from 1980 to 2030, is presented in nominal US dollars. This metric offers insight into the average economic output per person, highlighting the persistent challenges in improving living standards for the majority of the population.

### Economic Implications of Instability

The persistent conflicts have had a devastating impact, drastically reducing government [revenue](/Revenue) and escalating external debt. As Reyntjens aptly observed, "Entrepreneurs of insecurity are engaged in extractive activities that would be impossible in a stable state environment. The criminalization context in which these activities occur offers avenues for considerable factional and personal enrichment through the trafficking of arms, illegal drugs, toxic products, mineral resources and dirty money." Ethnic rivalries have been inflamed by economic interests, leading to rampant [looting](/Looting) and smuggling of coltan. Illegal [monopolies](/Monopoly) have taken root, often employing child labor for mining or forcing children into military service. National parks have been overrun by individuals seeking to exploit minerals and other resources. The increased poverty and hunger resulting from the war have driven the hunting of endangered wildlife. Education has been severely neglected under foreign control, and very few individuals have profited from the nation's mineral wealth. While the national resources are not the sole cause of the ongoing fighting, the competition over them has certainly become a powerful incentive to continue the conflict. The DRC's level of economic freedom is among the lowest globally, placing it squarely in the "repressed" category. Armed militias frequently clash with the government in the eastern regions, ostensibly over the mining sector or government corruption. Weak policies further contribute to economic instability. [Human rights](/Human_rights) abuses also severely impede economic activity. Despite a reported unemployment rate of 7%, the DRC still possesses one of the lowest GDPs per capita worldwide. A significant hurdle for aspiring entrepreneurs is the substantial minimum capital required to launch a company, often five times the average annual income. Furthermore, government-regulated prices can effectively force individuals to work for larger, more corrupt businesses simply to secure employment. The DRC faces considerable challenges in attracting foreign trade due to these regulatory barriers.

### International Relations

The persistent problems of poor [infrastructure](/Infrastructure), an unpredictable legal framework, widespread corruption, and a lack of transparency in government economic policies and financial operations continue to act as a significant brake on investment and economic growth. Numerous missions from the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) (IMF) and the [World Bank](/World_Bank) have met with the current government, aiming to assist in the development of a coherent economic plan. However, the reforms associated with these plans remain largely on hold.

Grappling with continuous currency depreciation, the government implemented a drastic measure in January 1999, banning the widespread use of U.S. dollars for all domestic commercial transactions, a stance it later softened. The government has consistently failed to provide adequate foreign exchange for economic transactions, resorting instead to printing money to finance its expenditures. Economic growth contracted in 2000, a consequence of the difficulty in meeting the stringent conditions set by international donors, persistently low prices for key export commodities, and the instability following a coup. The involvement of 125 companies in fueling the conflict in the DRC in 2003 underscores the deeply ingrained corruption within the nation.

