#### World Bank

With crucial assistance from the [International Development Association](/The_World_Bank_in_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo), the DRC has been making efforts to re-establish essential social services. This includes providing access to basic health services for 15 million people and distributing bed nets to combat the spread of malaria. Through the Emergency Demobilization and Reintegration Program, over 107,000 adult combatants and 34,000 child soldiers have been successfully demobilized. Travel time between [Lubumbashi](/Lubumbashi) and Kasomeno in [Katanga](/Katanga_Province) has been drastically reduced from seven days to just two hours, thanks to improved road infrastructure. This improvement has led to a significant 60% decrease in the prices of essential goods. With support from the IFC, KfW, and the EU, the DRC has streamlined its business environment, reducing the time required to register a business by 51%, cutting down the time for obtaining construction permits by 54%, and decreasing the number of taxes from an overwhelming 118 to just 30. Notable improvements have also been observed in the health sector, with the percentage of deliveries attended by trained staff jumping from 47% to 80%. In education, 14 million textbooks have been distributed to children, school completion rates have risen, and access to higher education has been expanded for students pursuing further studies.

#### International Monetary Fund

In 2015, the IMF was poised to offer a $1 billion loan to the DRC, following a two-year suspension of aid. This suspension was a consequence of the government's failure to provide adequate details regarding a mining deal involving one of its state-owned mines and an Israeli billionaire, [Dan Gertler](/Dan_Gertler). The loan was deemed potentially critical for the country, especially with presidential elections scheduled for December 2016, an event estimated to cost around $1.1 billion to fund. A significant logistical challenge for the elections was the sheer scale of reaching 68 million people spread across a country the size of Western Europe, with fewer than 1,860 miles of paved roads.

### Sectors

#### Agriculture

[Agriculture](/Agriculture_in_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo) remains the bedrock of the DRC's economy, accounting for a substantial 57.9% of the [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) in 1997. Key cash crops include [coffee](/Coffee), [palm oil](/Palm_oil), [rubber](/Rubber), [cotton](/Cotton), [sugar](/Sugar), [tea](/Tea), and [cocoa](/Cocoa_bean). Staple food crops consist of [cassava](/Cassava), [plantains](/Plantain_(cooking)), [maize](/Maize), [groundnuts](/Bambara_groundnut), and [rice](/Rice). In 1996, the agricultural sector was a major employer, providing jobs for 66% of the workforce.

In 2018, the Democratic Republic of Congo's agricultural output included:

*   29.9 million tons of [cassava](/Cassava) (ranking it the 3rd largest producer globally, behind Nigeria and Thailand).
*   4.7 million tons of [plantain](/Cooking_banana) (making it the world's largest producer).
*   2 million tons of [maize](/Maize).
*   1.1 million tons of [palm oil](/Palm_oil).
*   990 thousand tons of [rice](/Rice).
*   384 thousand tons of [sweet potato](/Sweet_potato).
*   309 thousand tons of [banana](/Banana).
*   307 thousand tons of [peanut](/Peanut).
*   213 thousand tons of [mango](/Mango) (including [mangosteen](/Mangosteen) and [guava](/Guava)).
*   213 thousand tons of [papaya](/Papaya).
*   205 thousand tons of [beans](/Beans).
*   186 thousand tons of [pineapple](/Pineapple).
*   168 thousand tons of [orange](/Orange_(fruit)).
*   101 thousand tons of [potato](/Potato).

In addition to these major crops, the DRC also produces smaller quantities of other agricultural products, such as [coffee](/Coffee) (29 thousand tons), [cocoa](/Cocoa_bean) (3.6 thousand tons), [natural rubber](/Natural_rubber) (14 thousand tons), and [tea](/Tea) (3.6 thousand tons).

#### Fishing

The Democratic Republic of Congo possesses an immense natural endowment, including 50 percent of Africa's forests and a vast river system that, according to a [United Nations](/United_Nations) report, could potentially supply [hydro-electric](/Hydro-electric) power to the entire continent, positioning the DRC as a significant economic power in [central Africa](/Central_Africa). Fish constitute the single most important source of animal protein for the Congolese population. In 2003, total production from marine, river, and lake fisheries was estimated at 222,965 tons, with the vast majority, over 5,000 tons, originating from inland waters. PEMARZA, a state-run agency, is responsible for marine fishing operations.

#### Forestry

Forests cover an extensive 60 percent of the DRC's total land area, representing a significant [timber](/Timber) resource. Commercial exploitation of the country's 61 million hectares (150 million acres) of exploitable wooded land is still in its nascent stages. The [Mayumbe area](/Mayumbe_area) in [Bas-Congo](/Bas-Congo) was once a primary center for timber extraction, but the forests in this region have been severely depleted. The more extensive forest regions located in the central cuvette and along the [Ubangi River](/Ubangi_River) valley have increasingly become targets for exploitation.

In 2003, roundwood removals were estimated at 72,170,000 cubic meters, with approximately 95 percent of this volume used for fuel. Currently, about 14 different timber species are being harvested. Exports of forest products in 2003 amounted to $25.7 million. The expansion of the forestry sector is contingent upon foreign capital investment, and the government acknowledges the necessity of changes in tax structures and export procedures to foster economic growth.

#### Mining

The DRC is exceptionally rich in minerals, yet it carries a burden of a history marred by predatory [mineral extraction](/Mining_industry_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo). This has been a recurring theme in the country's internal struggles for decades, particularly intensifying in the 1990s. While the economy of the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the second-largest nation in [Africa](/Africa), has historically leaned heavily on mining, its significance is no longer fully reflected in official [GDP](/GDP) data. This is largely due to the mining industry suffering from a prolonged period of an "uncertain legal framework, corruption, and a lack of transparency in government policy," a situation exacerbated by the pervasive [informal sector](/Informal_sector).

In her insightful book, *The Real Economy of Zaire*, MacGaffey described a parallel, often illicit economy, referred to as "system D," which operates entirely outside the official economic sphere (MacGaffey 1991:27). Consequently, this shadow economy remains unaccounted for in official [GDP](/GDP) calculations.

#### Energy

Thanks to its extensive river system, 86% of the country's electricity generation is hydroelectric. However, electricity access is largely confined to urban areas, and even there, less than half the population benefits from it. As of 2022, only 45% of the urban population and a mere 21.5% of the total population have access to electricity. For most households, charcoal remains the primary cooking fuel, accounting for over 70% of usage, and is almost exclusively used in [Kinshasa](/Kinshasa). Wood and other biomass sources follow at around 20%.

##### Exploitation of Mineral Substances by Companies

The Democratic Republic of Congo is a critical player in the [global battery supply chain](/Electric_vehicle_supply_chain). The economy of this vast African nation is heavily reliant on its mining sector. The Congo holds the distinction of being the world's largest producer of [cobalt](/Cobalt) ore and a major supplier of [copper](/Copper) and industrial [diamonds](/Diamond). It's estimated that the Congo possesses over 30% of the world's diamond reserves, primarily in the form of small, industrial-grade stones. [Coltan](/Coltan) is another crucial resource, serving as a primary source of [tantalum](/Tantalum), a vital component in the manufacturing of electronic devices like computers and mobile phones. In 2002, [tin](/Tin) deposits were discovered in the eastern part of the country, though mining operations have been on a small scale thus far. The Manono region in the central DRC harbors significant deposits of lithium and tin, along with tantalum and niobium, and is currently under development by an Australian company, with production anticipated in 2023. According to a 2011 report, the estimated total value of the DRC's major mineral reserves exceeded 300 billion US dollars at that time.

The illicit smuggling of [conflict minerals](/Conflict_minerals) such as [coltan](/Coltan) and [cassiterite](/Cassiterite) – the ores of [tantalum](/Tantalum) and [tin](/Tin), respectively – has been a significant factor in fueling the protracted conflict in Eastern Congo.

In contemporary times, larger mining companies are actively adapting to global demands for ESG (Environmental, Social, and Governance) standards and the [Initiative for Responsible Mining Assurance](/Initiative_for_Responsible_Mining_Assurance) (IRMA). A globally recognized certification is the 3T iTSCi system, which stands as the only widely implemented and accepted mineral traceability and due diligence framework in the region for 3T minerals—tin, tantalum, and tungsten. This system is internationally acknowledged for promoting responsible mining and traceability, aligning with the provisions of the 2010 Dodd-Frank Act. Currently, four Central African countries, including the DRC, are supplying legitimate and ethically sourced 3T minerals. ITSCi is unique in that its standards are 100% aligned with the OECD Guidance. Substantial progress has been made over the past 15 years, with the iTSCi initiative providing a support network for artisanal and small-scale miners, helping to establish and regulate the industry. By the close of 2019, ITSCi had registered 2,000 mines, employed approximately 80,000 miners, and facilitated the supply of over 2,000 tonnes of tin, tantalum, and tungsten minerals monthly. The initiative has indeed come a long way in the last decade. A comprehensive report by Pact in 2015, titled *Unconflicted: Making Conflict-Free Mining a Reality in the DRC, Rwanda and Burundi*, detailed the progress of iTSCi over the preceding five years, highlighting successes, ongoing challenges, and future work required.

###### Copper and Cobalt

[Katanga Mining Limited](/Katanga_Mining), a company headquartered in London, operates the Luilu Metallurgical Plant. This facility boasts a capacity of 175,000 tonnes of copper and 8,000 tonnes of cobalt annually, making it the largest cobalt refinery globally. Following a significant rehabilitation program, the company resumed copper production in December 2007 and commenced cobalt production in May 2008.

#### Informal Sector

A substantial portion of economic activity within the DRC takes place in the informal sector, a reality that means these contributions are not reflected in official GDP data.

#### Transport

Ground transportation within the Democratic Republic of Congo has consistently presented formidable challenges. The rugged terrain and climate of the [Congo Basin](/Congo_Basin) pose significant obstacles to the construction of roads and railways, compounded by the sheer vastness of the country. Furthermore, decades of chronic economic mismanagement and internal conflict have resulted in severe under-investment in transportation infrastructure over many years.

Conversely, the Democratic Republic of Congo possesses an extensive network of [navigable](/Navigable) [waterways](/Waterway), and historically, water transport has been the predominant mode for movement across approximately two-thirds of the nation.

